'''Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh''' [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire|OBE]] [[Writers to the Signet|WS]] [[Notary public|NP]] (born 5 October 1970) is a Scottish politician.  She was elected Member of Parliament (MP) for [[Ochil and South Perthshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Ochil and South Perthshire]] in May 2015, and has served as the [[Scottish National Party]] Trade and Investment spokesperson, Deputy Shadow Leader of the House in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], and the SNP's National Women's and Equalities Convener. She was defeated at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election]]. A solicitor and businessperson, and a former actress, Ahmed-Sheikh founded and formerly chaired the Scottish Asian Women's Association.

== Early life and education ==
Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh was born in [[Chelsea, London|Chelsea]], London in 1970, and raised in [[Edinburgh]]. Her mother is a half-Welsh, half-Czech actress who performed with the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]];<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/1999/may/04/gender.uk|title=The unlikely lassie |first=Libby |last=Brooks |work=The Guardian |date=4 May 1999 |accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref><ref name="mep">{{cite news|url=http://news.stv.tv/west-central/228304-tasmina-ahmed-sheikh-bids-to-be-first-asian-mep-for-scotland/|last=Mcleod|first=Kayleigh|title=Bollywood actress hopes to land dream role in European Parliament|date=6 June 2013|accessdate=26 April 2014|publisher=STV News}}</ref> her father, of Pakistani origin, was the first councillor of Asian background elected in Scotland—in 1986 for the New Town/Stockbridge ward on Lothian Regional Council, representing the Conservative Party.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/subst-style-2-x29-44-33p-leith-mixes-an-explosive-cocktail-1.808475|title=Leith mixes an explosive cocktail |date=16 December 1991|accessdate=1 February 2014|publisher=Herald & Times Group|work=HeraldScotland}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/electing-to-put-soap-on-the-ropes-tasmina-ahmed-sheikh-has-abandoned-her-acting-career-in-pakistan-to-fight-for-a-seat-in-the-scottish-parliament-frances-horsburgh-reports-1.304261|title=Electing to put soap on the ropes Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh has abandoned her acting career in Pakistan to fight for a seat in the Scottish Parliament |date=23 February 1999|accessdate=1 February 2014|publisher=Herald & Times Group|work=HeraldScotland}}</ref> Ahmed-Sheikh was educated at [[Craigmount High School]], [[George Heriot's School]] in Edinburgh, the [[University of Edinburgh]] (MA) and the [[University of Strathclyde]] (LLB & Postgraduate Diploma in Law).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/politics/scottish-politics/analysis-snp-bucks-trend-for-privately-educated-mps.126940798 | title=Analysis: SNP bucks trend for privately educated MPs | publisher=Herald & Times Group|work=HeraldScotland | author=David Leask | date=1 June 2015 | accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref>

==Acting career==
After graduating in law, Ahmed-Sheikh decided to try acting. Playing parts in drama serials, she starred in the [[Pakistani dramas|Pakistani drama series]] ''Des Pardes'' and also produced and appeared in ''[[The Castle: Aik Umeed]]''. These led to a series of local modelling shoots, and starring in a drama Ansoo playing the role of Emotional girl Imaan, produced by her husband Zulfikar Sheikh, who also worked in drama as Dr Aryan.<ref name=AryNews>{{cite web|url=http://arynews.tv/en/tasmina-ahmed-sheikh-pakistani-drama-serial-and-bollywood-actress-to-contest-in-uk-election|title=Pakistani drama serial actress Tasmina Ahmed Sheikh contesting UK election|publisher=Ary News|date=7 May 2015}}</ref>

==Legal career==
Ahmed-Sheikh decided to concentrate on her legal career, her family and politics instead of acting<ref name=AryNews/> and was a partner at the Glasgow law firm Hamilton Burns, specialising in commercial conveyancing and private client work, often with a family law or immigration element.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://safi4yes.wordpress.com/2014/02/07/women-in-the-law-tasmina-ahmed-sheikh|title=Scots Asians For YES to an Independent Scotland|date=7 February 2014|accessdate=27 May 2014|via=Wordpress|work =Scots Asians 4 Yes}}</ref>

On 15 January 2019, she was found guilty of professional misconduct by a Law Society Tribunal and fined £3000.<ref name=Fined>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-46881007|title=Ex-SNP MP fined for professional misconduct|publisher=BBC News|date=15 January 2019|access-date=15 January 2019}}</ref>

== Political career ==
Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh was active in the [[Scottish Conservative Party]] from the age of 10 and a member from 16.<ref name="butterfly">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1343298/Defector-to-SNP-is-political-butterfly.html|title=Defector to SNP 'is political butterfly' |first=Nick |last=Britten|date=16 June 2000|accessdate=26 April 2014|work=The Telegraph |publisher=Telegraph Media Group}}</ref> She was chairperson of Edinburgh Central Young Conservatives and deputy spokeswoman for the party on women and family issues and equal opportunities.<ref name="defect" /> She stood as the party's candidate in [[Glasgow Govan (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Glasgow Govan]] in the [[1999 Scottish Parliament election]],<ref name="defect">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/791467.stm|title=Tory defects to SNP|date=14 June 2000|accessdate=26 April 2014|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> where she came in third place with 2,343 votes (8.88%).
 
In 2000, she resigned from the Conservatives in response to [[William Hague]]'s "right wing" pronouncements on asylum seekers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/792019.stm|title=Tory defector blames Hague|date=15 June 2000|accessdate=26 April 2014|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> She briefly joined the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] before declaring that she would join the [[Scottish National Party]], and was welcomed as a 'defector'. Alex Salmond said he was "glad she had joined the party".<ref>{{cite web|title=Tory defector held Labour card|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/792414.stm|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=14 July 2016|date=15 June 2000}}</ref>

In July 2012, she joined the Advisory Board of [[Yes Scotland]], the cross-party campaign for [[Scottish independence]] ahead of the [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|upcoming referendum]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-18752141|title=Scottish independence: Yes campaign board announced|date=8 July 2012|accessdate=26 April 2014|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>

In May 2014 she was the third candidate on the SNP's list for the [[2014 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|European Parliament election]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.stv.tv/scotland/272322-scots-likely-to-vote-yes-if-they-think-tories-will-win-uk-election/|title=Scots likely to vote Yes if they think Tories will win UK election|date=21 April 2014|accessdate=26 April 2014|publisher=STV News}}</ref> but was unsuccessful in winning a seat.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/politics/political-news/snp-split-over-candidates-for-euro-election.21592221|title=SNP split over candidates for Euro election|last=Gordon|first=Tom|date=14 July 2013|accessdate=26 April 2014|publisher=Herald & Times Group|work=The Herald}}</ref>

In the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] she was elected to the UK Parliament in the [[Ochil and South Perthshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Ochil and South Perthshire]] constituency, earning 46% of the vote as the SNP took the seat from Labour incumbent [[Gordon Banks (politician)|Gordon Banks]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ochil & South Perthshire Parliamentary constituency|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/S14000050|accessdate=8 May 2015|publisher=BBC News|date=8 May 2015}}</ref> However she lost the seat at the following [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] to [[Luke Graham (politician)|Luke Graham]] of the [[Scottish Conservative Party]].{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}

In 2019 it was reported that The SNP declined her application to stand in the upcoming European Parliament elections of that year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/tasmina-ahmed-sheikh-s-bid-to-run-in-european-elections-is-rejected-0lpk3rws3|title=Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh’s bid to run in European elections is rejected|work=The Times|date=20 April 2019|publisher=Times Newspapers|author=Kieran Andrews}}
</ref>

== Charity work ==
Ahmed-Sheikh is the founder and chair of the Scottish Asian Women's Association (SAWA). The official launch of SAWA was on 19 April 2012 and the Scottish government provided support at a launch event at Stirling Castle, to the equivalent of around £16,000.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/13102697.Claims_of_SNP_cronyism_after_charity_handed_public_support/ |title=Claims of SNP cronyism after charity handed public support |first=Tom |last=Gordon |work=The Herald |publisher=Herald & Times Group |date=2 May 2013 |accessdate=12 June 2016}}</ref> Ahmed-Sheikh resigned as a trustee of SAWA after her election as a MP in 2015.<ref name="Herald 13Jan2016">{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/14199506.SNP_MP_facing_questions_over_charity_s_paltry_donations_to_good_causes/ |title=SNP MP Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh facing questions after charity she founded donates less than 3% of income to good causes |first=Tom |last=Gordon |work=The Herald |publisher=Herald & Times Group |date=13 January 2016 |accessdate=12 June 2016}}</ref>

In January 2016, ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]'' reported that during the period Ahmed-Sheikh was chair, only a small proportion (3%) of the SAWA's income had been donated to charitable causes.<ref name="Herald 13Jan2016"/> It was reported in May 2017, that the [[Law Society of Scotland]] is investigating "administrative matters" which relate her period as a solicitor and alleged "financial impropriety involving a trust fund set up to help a vulnerable person". [[Nicola Sturgeon]], Scottish first minister and SNP leader, is standing by Ahmed-Sheikh who has faced calls for her to be suspended from the party.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gourtsoyannis|first=Paris|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/general-election/nicola-sturgeon-backs-under-fire-tasmina-ahmed-sheikh-1-4447742|title=Nicola Sturgeon backs under fire Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh|work=The Scotsman|date=17 May 2017|accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cramb|first=Auslan|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/17/nicola-sturgeon-backs-tasmina-ahmed-sheikh-amid-renewed-calls/|title=Nicola Sturgeon backs Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh amid renewed calls for her suspension|work=The Telegraph|date=17 May 2017|accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref>

== Professional misconduct disciplinary case ==
In January 2019 Ahmed-Sheikh was fined £3,000 by the [[Scottish Solicitors' Discipline Tribunal]] for professional misconduct.<ref name=Fined/> The Tribunal found that Ahmed-Sheikh and fellow solicitor Alan Mickel had shown "disregard for the rules" in running a trust and had a conflict of interest when they borrowed money from it. In addition to their fines, the pair also had to pay the expenses of the [[Law Society of Scotland|Law Society]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/01/15/former-snp-mp-tasmina-ahmed-sheikh-guilty-professional-misconduct/|title=Former SNP MP Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh guilty of professional misconduct|date=15 January 2019|publisher=Telegraph Media Group|work = The Telegraph}}</ref>

== Media work ==
Ahmed-Sheikh is co-owner, along with [[Alex Salmond]], of Slainte Media, a production company which is behind ''[[The Alex Salmond Show]]'', and regularly co-hosts the programme on [[Russia Today]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://opencorporates.com/companies/gb/SC572513|title=Slainte Media Limited|date=25 October 2018|work=Open Corporates|access-date=15 January 2019}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-41941359 Nicola Sturgeon questions Alex Salmond's choice of Russian TV channel] BBC News, 10 November 2017 [https://web.archive.org/web/20171111004545/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-41941359 Archived] from the original on 11 November 2017; Retrieved 11 November 2017</ref>

== Personal life ==
A [[Muslim]], Ahmed-Sheikh is married to Zulfiqar Sheikh and they have four children—Elysée, Saif, Shansee, Vaneesee.<ref name=joyoframadanfasting>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/real-life/bollywood-star-snp-political-hopeful-2017044|title=Bollywood star and SNP political hopeful Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh reveals joys of Ramadan fasting|last=Johnston|first=Clare|date=2 July 2013|accessdate=26 April 2014|work=Daily Record}}</ref> She was appointed [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[2014 New Year Honours]] for services to business and to the Asian community in Scotland.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/honours-list/10542766/New-Year-Honours-2014-list-in-full.html|title=New Year Honours 2014: list in full|date=30 December 2013|accessdate=26 April 2014|publisher=Telegraph Media Group|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> She speaks English, French and [[Urdu]].{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}

